WEBVTT

00:03.699 --> 00:04.046
.

00:04.091 --> 00:05.266
[upbeat music]

00:05.309 --> 00:08.312
- People are irrational,

00:08.356 --> 00:10.662
but predictably so.

00:10.706 --> 00:13.448
We're more afraid
of flying than driving,

00:13.491 --> 00:17.017
when the fact is, driving
is much more dangerous.

00:17.060 --> 00:18.670
[tires squealing]

00:18.714 --> 00:20.846
We know we should eat
healthy food.

00:20.890 --> 00:23.719
But then we give in
to temptation.

00:24.937 --> 00:29.681
We buy things we'll never,
ever use.

00:29.725 --> 00:32.206
We assume people are making
rational decisions,

00:32.249 --> 00:34.121
weighing the pros and cons,

00:34.164 --> 00:36.427
when most of the time,
we're not.

00:36.471 --> 00:39.865
Instead, we rely on instincts,

00:39.909 --> 00:42.520
which are almost always wrong,

00:42.564 --> 00:45.871
sometimes dangerously wrong.

00:45.915 --> 00:48.309
♪

00:48.352 --> 00:51.964
One error in judgment leads
to another,

00:52.008 --> 00:56.056
which is why eventually,
someone ends up calling me.

00:56.099 --> 01:01.539
- ♪ Straight down the middle
until I'm lost ♪

01:01.583 --> 01:03.846
♪ Watch me walk

01:05.282 --> 01:07.676
- Any ideas?

01:07.719 --> 01:09.286
- [over radio]
This is an FBI scene.

01:09.330 --> 01:10.635
Virginia Troopers
and DC Police,

01:10.679 --> 01:12.942
stand by for FBI instructions.

01:12.985 --> 01:14.639
[helicopter buzzes]

01:14.683 --> 01:17.773
[tense music]

01:17.816 --> 01:22.430
♪

01:22.473 --> 01:24.649
- Hi, Clay. My name is Alec.

01:24.693 --> 01:25.433
[baby crying softly]

01:25.476 --> 01:27.174
- You another negotiator?

01:27.217 --> 01:28.392
- [chuckles] No.

01:28.436 --> 01:29.741
I would never work
in law enforcement.

01:29.785 --> 01:31.569
It pays crap,
and that's saying something

01:31.613 --> 01:34.006
coming from
a college professor.

01:34.050 --> 01:36.357
Congratulations, by the way.
The FBI only brings me in

01:36.400 --> 01:38.009
when they're really screwed.

01:38.054 --> 01:41.101
I have to say, I'm impressed.

01:41.144 --> 01:43.277
Most people who try this kind
of thing get arrested

01:43.320 --> 01:45.235
or killed,
but you were smart about it,

01:45.279 --> 01:46.366
with the baby and all.

01:46.410 --> 01:48.586
- I want what I asked for.

01:48.630 --> 01:50.588
- Don't worry.
You'll get it.

01:50.632 --> 01:52.068
- The guy's a killer.
We can't give--

01:52.112 --> 01:53.374
- Just let him try.

01:54.723 --> 01:56.594
- I have spoken
to the higher-ups.

01:56.638 --> 01:58.247
We're authorizing a helicopter.

01:58.292 --> 02:00.120
- [whispers] We are not
authorizing a helicopter.

02:00.163 --> 02:01.338
- What I want to know
from you is,

02:01.382 --> 02:02.992
what kind of helicopter
do you want?

02:03.035 --> 02:06.561
- [breathing shakily]

02:06.604 --> 02:07.649
What kind?

02:07.692 --> 02:08.824
- I've been doing
some research.

02:08.866 --> 02:10.304
It looks like
the Sikorsky is faster,

02:10.347 --> 02:12.393
but the Airbus has
a longer range.

02:12.436 --> 02:13.785
Do you have a preference?

02:15.004 --> 02:16.962
- Uh...

02:17.006 --> 02:18.138
Sikorsky.

02:18.181 --> 02:19.269
- Done.

02:19.313 --> 02:20.270
- I hope you know
what you're doing.

02:20.314 --> 02:21.837
- Now, the Sikorsky will
get you

02:21.880 --> 02:22.881
a couple hundred miles,

02:22.925 --> 02:25.579
but when you land,

02:25.623 --> 02:27.538
you might have
to kill the pilot, right?

02:28.844 --> 02:30.019
- Say again?

02:30.062 --> 02:31.847
- You could try
to swear him to secrecy,

02:31.890 --> 02:33.240
but probably you're gonna
have to kill him.

02:33.283 --> 02:35.198
You know how you'll
dispose of the body?

02:35.242 --> 02:37.200
Never mind.
You'll figure it out.

02:37.244 --> 02:40.551
But you do need a plan
for the baby.

02:40.595 --> 02:44.033
Is she on breast milk
or formula?

02:44.076 --> 02:45.991
[baby fussing]

02:46.035 --> 02:48.820
♪

02:48.864 --> 02:50.648
That's, of course, if you're
planning to hold onto her.

02:50.692 --> 02:51.649
- Shh.

02:51.692 --> 02:53.303
- You can put her
in a dumpster.

02:53.347 --> 02:58.003
Babies can survive for 24,
maybe 48 hours,

02:58.047 --> 02:59.483
depending on how cold it gets.

02:59.527 --> 03:01.224
We can get you
some extra blankets.

03:01.268 --> 03:03.095
- Please, just let me hold her.

03:03.139 --> 03:04.793
- [yells]
Would you shut up, lady?

03:04.836 --> 03:07.056
- Might be easier
if you leave the baby here.

03:07.099 --> 03:09.145
But without her,
I gotta be honest,

03:09.189 --> 03:10.886
you won't have much leverage.

03:10.929 --> 03:12.844
When the helicopter gets here,
do you want it to land

03:12.888 --> 03:14.368
on the roof
or in the parking lot?

03:14.411 --> 03:16.805
[baby crying]

03:16.848 --> 03:18.372
I can walk through the pros
and cons if you like.

03:18.415 --> 03:20.852
[siren wails]

03:20.896 --> 03:24.029
♪

03:24.073 --> 03:25.248
- Got a clean shot.

03:26.902 --> 03:28.382
- Hold your fire.

03:30.819 --> 03:34.388
[baby crying]

03:54.843 --> 03:56.453
- Good choice.

04:06.985 --> 04:07.899
- Thanks a lot, man.

04:07.943 --> 04:09.423
- Hey.

04:09.466 --> 04:10.511
What was it you did back there?

04:10.554 --> 04:12.382
- Paradoxical persuasion.

04:12.426 --> 04:14.602
I overly embraced his idea
to force him

04:14.645 --> 04:16.255
to think it through enough
to realize

04:16.298 --> 04:17.779
it was a terrible idea.

04:17.822 --> 04:19.214
- And how did you know he
wasn't gonna pull the trigger?

04:19.259 --> 04:21.478
- It works about 95%
of the time.

04:21.522 --> 04:22.827
- And the other 5%?

04:22.871 --> 04:24.568
- There's always outliers,
Marisa.

04:24.612 --> 04:25.961
- And what if he had been
an outlier?

04:26.004 --> 04:27.702
- He probably would have
shot someone.

04:27.745 --> 04:29.834
If it helps,
statistically speaking,

04:29.878 --> 04:31.314
more likely one of us
than the baby.

04:31.358 --> 04:33.142
- That ability that you have

04:33.185 --> 04:36.972
to completely divorce emotion
from reason is both

04:37.015 --> 04:39.322
why I married you and why--

04:39.366 --> 04:40.845
- You're no longer married
to me.

04:42.151 --> 04:43.457
- Why we split up.

04:45.720 --> 04:47.635
Tell your sister I said hello.

04:55.164 --> 04:56.165
[engine turns over]

04:56.207 --> 04:57.558
[Duckwrth's "Unstatus Quo"]

04:57.601 --> 04:59.037
- ♪ Whatcha here for?
Now, tell me ♪

04:59.081 --> 05:01.344
♪ Say, whatcha here for?
Now, tell me ♪

05:01.388 --> 05:02.563
♪ Say, whatcha here for? Nah

05:02.606 --> 05:03.607
♪ Uh

05:03.651 --> 05:05.174
♪ What's up? Uh

05:05.217 --> 05:07.176
♪ I see you standing

05:07.219 --> 05:09.526
♪ With your back
on the brick wall ♪

05:09.570 --> 05:11.223
♪ But I know
you wanna lift off ♪

05:11.267 --> 05:12.137
♪ Well, here's your chance

05:12.181 --> 05:13.791
♪ I'm likely

05:13.835 --> 05:15.880
♪ The reason you might be

05:15.924 --> 05:18.056
♪ Moving on the right league

05:18.100 --> 05:21.146
♪ Sweeter than icy,
where the hook at? ♪

05:21.190 --> 05:23.584
♪ I don't know
what you came to do ♪

05:23.627 --> 05:25.412
♪ I don't know
what you came here for ♪

05:25.455 --> 05:26.674
- Good morning, Professor.

05:26.717 --> 05:27.892
I have the surveys ready
for the intro class,

05:27.936 --> 05:29.503
and I put together
a pie chart for you

05:29.546 --> 05:30.808
with the demographic breakdown.

05:30.852 --> 05:32.636
Uh, this is Rizwan.
Today's his first day.

05:32.680 --> 05:33.811
- I just want to say
what a privilege it is

05:33.855 --> 05:35.117
to join
your research assistant team.

05:35.159 --> 05:36.466
- Phoebe showing you the ropes?

05:36.510 --> 05:38.120
- He's up to speed--mostly.

05:38.163 --> 05:40.252
"The Post" wants a quote about
the mafia guy you flipped.

05:40.296 --> 05:42.429
Should I give them the one
about conflicting motivations?

05:42.472 --> 05:44.213
- I'll call them back.
Anything else?

05:44.256 --> 05:45.780
- My roommate wants to know
if you really helped

05:45.823 --> 05:46.868
the Rams win the Super Bowl.

05:46.911 --> 05:48.260
- Well, that was
a risky experiment,

05:48.304 --> 05:49.610
but it worked out for them.

05:50.393 --> 05:51.394
Hello, hello.

05:51.438 --> 05:52.656
I'm Alec Mercer.

05:52.700 --> 05:55.572
Welcome
to Applied Psychology 101.

05:55.616 --> 05:59.010
If you're wondering
about what happened to my face,

05:59.054 --> 06:01.404
it wasn't one
of my experiments.

06:01.448 --> 06:04.712
I was burned many years ago
on over 60% of my body.

06:04.755 --> 06:07.192
And for the better part
of three years,

06:07.236 --> 06:11.283
I was in the hospital with
my body covered with bandages,

06:11.327 --> 06:13.547
which were changed every day.

06:13.590 --> 06:17.115
I-it was, as you can imagine,
very painful.

06:17.159 --> 06:18.639
And the nurses believed

06:18.682 --> 06:21.990
that ripping the bandages off
quickly was much better

06:22.033 --> 06:23.426
than doing it slowly.

06:23.470 --> 06:25.950
I disagreed,
but they wouldn't listen.

06:25.994 --> 06:28.126
I became deeply intrigued
by this idea

06:28.170 --> 06:31.695
that we repeatedly
and predictably make

06:31.739 --> 06:34.698
the wrong decisions
in many aspects of our lives.

06:34.742 --> 06:38.528
And research could help
change these patterns.

06:38.572 --> 06:40.095
I began doing experiments.

06:40.138 --> 06:43.707
And I found
the nurses were wrong.

06:43.751 --> 06:45.666
So I went back,
and I told them.

06:45.709 --> 06:47.494
And they promised
that they would

06:47.537 --> 06:49.800
change their practices.

06:49.844 --> 06:53.325
One nurse admitted
that she simply assumed

06:53.369 --> 06:56.894
that fast was better,
because for the nurses,

06:56.938 --> 07:02.770
inflicting that pain slowly
was much worse.

07:02.813 --> 07:05.555
I had never considered
their pain.

07:06.817 --> 07:08.689
There are great lessons
to be learned in this.

07:08.732 --> 07:10.299
- [whispering indistinctly]

07:10.342 --> 07:11.692
- Do you have a question?

07:12.823 --> 07:15.435
- Yeah, uh, how'd it happen,

07:15.478 --> 07:17.654
you know, your burns?

07:17.698 --> 07:21.005
[dramatic music]

07:21.049 --> 07:23.573
♪

07:23.617 --> 07:25.967
- [groaning]

07:27.577 --> 07:28.796
Drag racing.

07:28.839 --> 07:31.320
I ran right off the road.
Gas tank exploded.

07:31.363 --> 07:33.104
Anyway, let's get started.

07:33.148 --> 07:34.018
[elevator dings]

07:34.062 --> 07:35.933
[chuckling]
- Drag racing?

07:35.977 --> 07:37.500
- I was gonna go
with tiki dancing--

07:37.544 --> 07:39.371
Hawaiian luau
that got out of hand.

07:39.415 --> 07:41.678
- Why not just tell them
the truth?

07:42.853 --> 07:44.986
- When I remember
all of it, I will.

07:47.554 --> 07:49.469
[phone ringing]
- Uh, Professor.

07:51.645 --> 07:52.602
- This is Alec.

07:52.646 --> 07:54.430
[intriguing music]

07:54.474 --> 07:56.214
Madam Mayor.
I'll be right there.

07:56.258 --> 08:00.654
♪

08:00.697 --> 08:02.786
- A young woman
named Jasmine Curtland

08:02.830 --> 08:04.048
was murdered last night.

08:04.092 --> 08:06.137
The suspect is
her ex-boyfriend,

08:06.181 --> 08:09.532
Dylan Hayes,
son of Senator Laura Hayes.

08:09.576 --> 08:12.840
Laura is a friend
and a political ally.

08:12.883 --> 08:15.495
Even the allegations could
blow up her campaign.

08:15.538 --> 08:17.497
And any delay
in charging will smack

08:17.540 --> 08:18.715
of preferential treatment.

08:18.759 --> 08:22.327
- Because it is
preferential treatment.

08:22.371 --> 08:23.415
I'm not interested.

08:23.459 --> 08:24.852
- Alec, I know Dylan.

08:24.895 --> 08:26.114
Known him since he was a baby.

08:26.157 --> 08:28.377
He's a good kid.
No criminal record.

08:28.420 --> 08:30.988
- You've got plenty
of resources at your disposal,

08:31.032 --> 08:31.859
as does he.

08:31.902 --> 08:33.469
- He's a damn war hero.

08:33.513 --> 08:34.905
Served with the Marines.

08:34.948 --> 08:37.299
Honorable discharge
when his Humvee was hit

08:37.342 --> 08:38.605
with an IED in Afghanistan.

08:38.648 --> 08:40.607
He's the only one who lived.

08:40.650 --> 08:41.999
- Was he treated for PTSD?

08:42.043 --> 08:44.131
- I don't know.
I do know he developed

08:44.174 --> 08:46.787
a drinking problem,
but he was in AA

08:46.830 --> 08:48.658
and no history of violence.

08:48.702 --> 08:49.833
- What do you need me to do?

08:49.877 --> 08:51.574
- I need to know if he's guilty

08:51.618 --> 08:53.663
faster than the wheels
of justice turn.

08:53.707 --> 08:56.361
If he didn't do it,
I'll do whatever it takes

08:56.405 --> 08:57.580
to keep his name
out of the press.

08:57.624 --> 08:58.973
- And if he did?

08:59.016 --> 09:02.367
- I will tell the DA
to move ahead full force.

09:02.411 --> 09:04.413
I've instructed
the department to give you

09:04.456 --> 09:06.241
all the access you need.

09:06.284 --> 09:08.417
They're waiting
for you downstairs.

09:08.460 --> 09:11.376
[tense music]

09:11.420 --> 09:16.077
♪

09:16.120 --> 09:17.731
- I did it.

09:17.774 --> 09:19.515
I killed Jasmine.

09:19.559 --> 09:21.604
- Where's his lawyer?

09:21.648 --> 09:22.866
- Well, he had
a whole army with him,

09:22.910 --> 09:25.173
but he just fired 'em.

09:25.216 --> 09:26.261
- Start at the beginning.

09:28.393 --> 09:31.005
- I was having a rough night.

09:31.048 --> 09:34.051
It was the anniversary of the
attack where my friends died.

09:34.095 --> 09:35.749
I wanted to drink,
but I went to a meeting instead

09:35.792 --> 09:37.707
at St. Mel's on 45th.

09:37.751 --> 09:39.970
I had a Coke, slice of pizza.

09:40.014 --> 09:42.712
Thought I was okay,
but I guess I wasn't.

09:42.756 --> 09:45.540
I ended up at some bar.

09:45.585 --> 09:47.108
Ordered a beer,

09:47.151 --> 09:48.196
then another.

09:48.239 --> 09:49.676
Realized I was near
Jasmine's place,

09:49.719 --> 09:50.894
so I walked over.

09:50.938 --> 09:52.983
- Jasmine's your ex-girlfriend?
- Mm-hmm.

09:53.027 --> 09:54.071
- She break things off
with you,

09:54.115 --> 09:55.725
or was it the other way around?

09:55.769 --> 09:59.381
- We were kind of
on again, off again.

09:59.424 --> 10:02.427
She thought I needed
to work through some stuff.

10:02.471 --> 10:03.472
She was probably right.

10:03.515 --> 10:05.648
- What happened next?

10:05.692 --> 10:07.694
- One thing led to another.
We had sex.

10:08.869 --> 10:10.348
- Did you use a condom?

10:10.392 --> 10:12.263
- I, uh--yeah.

10:12.307 --> 10:13.351
Think so.

10:13.395 --> 10:15.615
- In what position
did you have sex?

10:15.658 --> 10:17.138
Traditional missionary--

10:17.181 --> 10:19.096
- [clears throat]
I think we get the picture.

10:19.140 --> 10:20.794
So what happened?
Did you get in a fight?

10:20.837 --> 10:22.622
- I guess.
- You guess?

10:22.665 --> 10:23.753
- Yeah. We got in a fight.

10:23.797 --> 10:25.755
She said it was really over
this time.

10:25.799 --> 10:27.278
I must've snapped.

10:28.366 --> 10:29.803
- You own a gun?

10:29.846 --> 10:31.195
Did you have it with you
last night?

10:31.239 --> 10:33.284
- No.
The gun was Jasmine's

10:33.328 --> 10:34.982
for protection.

10:35.025 --> 10:36.853
She had a stalker once.

10:39.421 --> 10:40.857
I should've been
the one protecting her,

10:40.901 --> 10:42.946
not the one
she needed protection from.

10:42.990 --> 10:45.732
- So how did her gun end up
in your hands?

10:45.775 --> 10:47.777
- One thing led to another,
I guess.

10:47.821 --> 10:48.996
- You said that before.

10:49.039 --> 10:51.259
- The gun just--just went off.

10:51.302 --> 10:52.564
- What kind of gun?

10:52.608 --> 10:54.131
A Glock?

10:54.175 --> 10:55.480
SIG Sauer?

10:55.524 --> 10:57.134
- I don't--I--I don't remember.

10:57.178 --> 10:58.701
- What'd you do
with the gun after?

10:58.745 --> 10:59.833
- I don't know.

10:59.876 --> 11:01.617
- Why'd you take
her sweatshirt off?

11:01.661 --> 11:02.836
- [yells] I don't know, okay?

11:02.879 --> 11:04.315
I blacked out.

11:04.359 --> 11:05.665
I woke up in my car.

11:05.708 --> 11:07.101
There was all this blood.
I was scared.

11:07.144 --> 11:08.537
I went to Jasmine's place,

11:08.580 --> 11:10.582
and I--and I found her.

11:10.626 --> 11:11.758
- Have you blacked out before?

11:11.801 --> 11:13.324
- [sniffling]

11:15.849 --> 11:18.678
- How did it feel?

11:18.721 --> 11:20.331
When you shot her.

11:20.375 --> 11:22.116
Did you feel scared?

11:22.159 --> 11:24.379
Feel angry?

11:25.728 --> 11:28.339
Did it feel empowering?

11:28.383 --> 11:30.472
Dylan. Dylan.

11:30.515 --> 11:32.430
Try.

11:32.474 --> 11:34.084
Try to recall.

11:36.391 --> 11:38.741
- I don't--I don't know.

11:38.785 --> 11:40.917
I--I just remember
pulling the trigger.

11:40.961 --> 11:46.793
♪

11:46.836 --> 11:48.359
- Well, I guess that's that.

11:48.403 --> 11:49.534
- You think he did it?

11:49.578 --> 11:50.884
You realize that you're talking

11:50.927 --> 11:53.364
about sending a man
to prison for life, right?

11:53.408 --> 11:54.365
- Well, he confessed.

11:54.409 --> 11:55.497
- He did.

11:55.540 --> 11:57.455
But I think he was mistaken.

11:57.499 --> 12:00.284
When we remember things,
we remember images,

12:00.328 --> 12:02.156
specific details.

12:02.199 --> 12:03.897
He went to a meeting
at St. Mel's.

12:03.940 --> 12:05.942
He drank a Coke.
He ate a slice of pizza.

12:05.986 --> 12:07.465
All that he recalled easily.

12:07.509 --> 12:10.164
But when he talked about
what happened in the apartment,

12:10.207 --> 12:11.774
different story.

12:11.818 --> 12:14.559
He kept repeating the phrase,
"one thing led to another."

12:14.603 --> 12:16.039
He couldn't remember

12:16.083 --> 12:17.737
whether he wore a condom
when they had sex.

12:17.780 --> 12:19.956
A former Marine
couldn't remember

12:20.000 --> 12:21.915
what kind of gun he fired.

12:21.958 --> 12:23.743
Doesn't add up.

12:23.786 --> 12:25.309
The real question is,

12:25.353 --> 12:28.965
why would somebody confess
to a murder he didn't commit?

12:32.360 --> 12:32.534
.

12:32.577 --> 12:33.840
[indistinct chatter]

12:33.883 --> 12:35.972
[indistinct radio chatter]

12:36.016 --> 12:37.321
- Hey, hey.

12:38.496 --> 12:39.889
- I got your text.
Why am I here?

12:39.933 --> 12:42.022
- I convinced the mayor
to give me 48 hours

12:42.065 --> 12:43.458
to prove
Dylan Hayes is innocent.

12:43.501 --> 12:45.895
She said the FBI was involved,
so I called the FBI.

12:45.939 --> 12:47.462
- You didn't call the FBI.
You called me.

12:47.505 --> 12:48.593
- You called me
for that hostage thing.

12:48.637 --> 12:49.594
- Barry called you for that.

12:49.638 --> 12:50.813
- You want me to call Barry?

12:50.857 --> 12:52.510
- You want to fill me in?

12:54.338 --> 12:56.123
- Marisa.
Good to see you again.

12:56.165 --> 12:57.733
- Elise Bowen,
District Attorney.

12:57.777 --> 12:59.256
This is Alec Mercer.

12:59.300 --> 13:01.476
- The mayor told me about you.
You're the science guy.

13:01.519 --> 13:02.694
- That's Bill Nye.

13:02.738 --> 13:04.435
I'm actually
the behavioral science guy.

13:04.479 --> 13:06.481
- Can you tell us
what happened?

13:06.524 --> 13:08.048
- She was shot in the chest
at close range.

13:08.091 --> 13:09.136
No forced entry.

13:09.179 --> 13:10.398
Probably knew her attacker,

13:10.441 --> 13:12.139
or wasn't afraid of him,
at any rate.

13:12.182 --> 13:13.705
- And the, uh--

13:13.749 --> 13:15.098
- The bullet went
through her chest

13:15.142 --> 13:17.144
into a display full
of pressurized hair mousse,

13:17.187 --> 13:18.623
and a couple cans exploded.

13:18.667 --> 13:21.148
- Is that an AA sobriety chip?

13:21.191 --> 13:23.411
- Dylan said
he and Jasmine met in AA.

13:24.891 --> 13:26.022
That a webcam?

13:26.066 --> 13:27.197
- Influencer.

13:27.241 --> 13:28.677
Makeup and hair products
mostly.

13:28.720 --> 13:30.374
Anyway, we're just about
wrapped up.

13:30.418 --> 13:31.985
This case is pretty
cut-and-dried.

13:32.028 --> 13:34.117
- You think so?

13:34.161 --> 13:35.249
- The guy confessed.

13:35.292 --> 13:37.164
- If Dylan told you
he was innocent,

13:37.207 --> 13:38.295
would you take his word for it?

13:38.339 --> 13:41.516
- Well, no, but...

13:41.559 --> 13:42.996
- From a psychological
point of view,

13:43.039 --> 13:44.040
it's very strange.

13:44.084 --> 13:45.346
- I can ask for a polygraph.

13:45.389 --> 13:46.651
- That's useless in this case.

13:46.695 --> 13:48.218
He obviously thinks
he killed her.

13:48.262 --> 13:50.873
- Why would he remember doing
something he didn't do?

13:50.917 --> 13:53.397
- Last month,
a two-year-old in Texas died

13:53.441 --> 13:54.877
from being left
in a hot car all day.

13:54.921 --> 13:57.358
The father was certain
he dropped her off at daycare.

13:57.401 --> 13:59.534
He remembered doing it.

13:59.577 --> 14:01.014
- That's awful,
but how does that--

14:01.057 --> 14:02.319
- Memory is fallible.

14:02.363 --> 14:03.538
We make mistakes,

14:03.581 --> 14:05.322
sometimes tragic,
life-altering mistakes,

14:05.366 --> 14:07.890
when we count on memory
when we shouldn't.

14:07.934 --> 14:09.544
- So if Dylan didn't
kill Jasmine,

14:09.587 --> 14:11.589
what do you think
happened here?

14:11.633 --> 14:13.722
- I know where I'd start.

14:13.765 --> 14:15.724
- And what is so great
about this lip gloss

14:15.767 --> 14:17.769
by my hot new sponsor brand,
Cinnamon,

14:17.813 --> 14:20.555
is that it literally goes
with anything.

14:20.598 --> 14:21.599
Date night, girls' night...
- Ooh.

14:21.643 --> 14:24.559
She's right about
that lip gloss.

14:24.602 --> 14:26.213
- She's an influencer.

14:26.256 --> 14:27.910
You're being influenced,
little sister.

14:27.954 --> 14:29.346
- Okay.

14:29.390 --> 14:31.218
- How popular is she?

14:31.261 --> 14:34.351
- She's got
over 250,000 followers.

14:34.395 --> 14:36.136
- Any of 'em possible stalkers?

14:36.179 --> 14:38.790
- [chuckles]
Pretty much all of them.

14:41.141 --> 14:42.620
- Kylie.
- Hm?

14:42.664 --> 14:44.100
- You remember
when you were seven

14:44.144 --> 14:45.928
and you got lost in the mall?

14:45.972 --> 14:47.016
- Kind of.

14:47.060 --> 14:48.061
- It was the three of us.

14:48.104 --> 14:49.366
It was the week before school.

14:49.410 --> 14:50.977
You disappeared in Macy's,

14:51.020 --> 14:53.936
and we finally found you next
to the frozen yogurt stand.

14:53.980 --> 14:55.895
- Oh, yeah.

14:55.938 --> 14:57.940
Mom was wearing
that yellow dress, right?

14:57.984 --> 15:00.247
- I don't know.

15:00.290 --> 15:02.379
It never happened.

15:02.423 --> 15:03.990
- Then why did you say that?

15:04.033 --> 15:06.601
- There was this experiment
done in the 1990s.

15:06.644 --> 15:08.864
They convinced scores of adults

15:08.908 --> 15:10.735
that they were lost in the mall
as children

15:10.779 --> 15:13.434
to prove how easy it is
to trick our minds

15:13.477 --> 15:15.262
into remembering things.

15:15.305 --> 15:17.612
It is surprisingly easy.

15:17.655 --> 15:20.571
- For us easily influenced
mortals, you mean.

15:21.659 --> 15:23.400
You want some dinner?

15:23.444 --> 15:25.489
- That's not dinner.
That's barely food.

15:25.533 --> 15:27.404
Why are you eating
processed pasta

15:27.448 --> 15:28.928
designed for toddlers?

15:28.971 --> 15:31.234
- You study human behavior.
You tell me.

15:31.278 --> 15:33.367
- You are outside
my field of study.

15:33.410 --> 15:35.064
- You know, you could get
your own place.

15:35.108 --> 15:37.023
But you chose to move in
with your little sister,

15:37.066 --> 15:38.807
so you get what you get.

15:38.850 --> 15:41.549
- This living arrangement is
temporary.

15:41.592 --> 15:43.725
- Until what?

15:43.768 --> 15:46.858
Until Marisa takes you back?

15:46.902 --> 15:48.034
- Ooh.

15:50.819 --> 15:52.864
- Are you sure
I wasn't lost in the mall?

15:54.214 --> 15:55.998
- There's no consequence

15:56.042 --> 15:58.870
to you accepting
that you were lost in the mall.

15:58.914 --> 16:01.482
No associated guilt,
no penalty.

16:01.525 --> 16:03.614
[pensive music]

16:03.658 --> 16:05.486
Do you have more of those?

16:07.227 --> 16:08.532
- What do you want them for?

16:08.576 --> 16:10.447
- An experiment.

16:12.058 --> 16:14.277
Thanks for meeting me here.

16:14.321 --> 16:15.322
- No problem.

16:15.365 --> 16:16.758
But what's this all about?

16:16.801 --> 16:19.674
- I wanted to better understand
how memory works,

16:19.717 --> 16:22.024
specifically, how hard
it would be to convince

16:22.068 --> 16:24.853
someone like Dylan he'd
committed a crime if he hadn't.

16:24.896 --> 16:26.942
So I ran a little experiment.

16:26.986 --> 16:29.597
I started with
"lost in the mall,"

16:29.640 --> 16:31.120
and I took it a step further.

16:31.164 --> 16:33.340
I told them we were looking
at how we spend money.

16:33.383 --> 16:36.908
I gave each of them $50
and a small shopping cart,

16:36.952 --> 16:39.085
and I instructed them
that they had two minutes

16:39.128 --> 16:40.956
to get as much food
as they could.

16:41.000 --> 16:43.045
- What does that have to do
with Dylan's murder charge?

16:43.089 --> 16:43.959
- I'm getting to that.

16:44.003 --> 16:45.743
The shopping was just a ruse.

16:45.787 --> 16:47.354
Do you remember when you were
pushing the shopping cart

16:47.397 --> 16:49.443
down the hallway,
there was a table

16:49.486 --> 16:51.358
full of lab equipment nearby?

16:51.401 --> 16:53.621
That was very expensive
equipment.

16:53.664 --> 16:55.492
And when you walked by
with your shopping cart,

16:55.536 --> 16:57.407
you scratched it.

16:57.451 --> 16:59.105
- Are you sure?
- I'm afraid so.

16:59.148 --> 17:00.367
It's on video.

17:00.410 --> 17:01.455
They all confessed.

17:01.498 --> 17:02.717
- I'm so sorry.

17:02.760 --> 17:03.892
- Is this gonna
affect my grade?

17:03.935 --> 17:05.023
- Are you gonna
call my parents?

17:05.067 --> 17:06.808
- Okay, yeah, I did it.
But come on.

17:06.851 --> 17:09.289
Who leaves expensive lab
equipment in a hallway anyway?

17:09.332 --> 17:10.377
- Every single one
of them confessed

17:10.420 --> 17:11.682
to something they didn't do,

17:11.726 --> 17:13.031
just like Dylan did.

17:13.075 --> 17:14.729
- They didn't confess
to murder.

17:14.771 --> 17:17.123
- Anyone can confess
to anything

17:17.165 --> 17:19.429
given the right circumstances.

17:19.473 --> 17:21.474
If Dylan didn't do this,

17:21.518 --> 17:24.608
whoever did it is
still out there.

17:29.048 --> 17:29.222
.

17:29.265 --> 17:32.007
[soft dramatic music]

17:32.051 --> 17:37.012
♪

17:37.056 --> 17:40.755
- You know,
sushi doesn't travel well.

17:40.798 --> 17:42.409
- Oh, sorry.

17:42.452 --> 17:43.410
I meant to meet you.

17:43.453 --> 17:44.933
- Mm.
- I lost track of time.

17:44.976 --> 17:46.978
- You're starting
to run up a tab, bro.

17:48.632 --> 17:49.807
What is it?

17:52.636 --> 17:54.290
- Wes Banning is up for parole.

17:54.334 --> 17:55.596
- No.

17:55.639 --> 17:57.598
- The hearing's this week.

17:57.641 --> 18:00.122
"The suspected lone wolf
attacker was convicted

18:00.166 --> 18:02.037
"of two counts
of federal hate crimes

18:02.081 --> 18:04.474
"for possessing explosives
and building the bomb

18:04.518 --> 18:06.650
that killed 13 people."

18:06.694 --> 18:08.826
- And injured one.

18:10.001 --> 18:12.439
I can't believe they'd even
consider letting that man out.

18:12.482 --> 18:15.137
- They have to,
because he was never convicted

18:15.181 --> 18:17.008
of the murders themselves.

18:17.052 --> 18:18.358
Because--
- They couldn't place him

18:18.401 --> 18:19.881
at the scene.

18:19.924 --> 18:22.710
- You mean Icouldn't
place him at the scene.

18:22.753 --> 18:26.801
- Alec, it's been
almost 20 years.

18:26.844 --> 18:29.151
You have to stop
holding onto that.

18:29.195 --> 18:32.546
- It left a rather lasting
impression.

18:37.551 --> 18:38.726
I may not remember my past,

18:38.769 --> 18:42.773
but maybe I can help
Dylan remember his.

18:42.817 --> 18:44.645
- Okay, so not the same thing.

18:44.688 --> 18:47.735
Dylan doesn't remember
because he was drunk.

18:47.778 --> 18:50.477
And alcoholics tend to lie.

18:50.520 --> 18:52.305
[intriguing music]

18:52.348 --> 18:53.610
- There's one place they don't.

18:53.654 --> 18:55.482
- What do you mean?

18:55.525 --> 18:56.787
♪

18:56.831 --> 18:58.659
[scoffs] Hello?

18:58.702 --> 18:59.660
Where are you going?

18:59.703 --> 19:01.140
- To a meeting.

19:01.183 --> 19:04.839
♪

19:04.882 --> 19:06.014
- Professor?

19:06.057 --> 19:07.842
- Oh, good.
You're here.

19:07.885 --> 19:09.104
- Where's Phoebe?

19:09.148 --> 19:10.366
- She's still
a bit peeved at me

19:10.410 --> 19:11.585
for the shopping cart
experiment.

19:11.628 --> 19:13.195
I put her in charge
of the lab tonight

19:13.239 --> 19:15.676
to restore
her sense of control.

19:15.719 --> 19:17.895
You're new, so I thought
you would enjoy seeing

19:17.939 --> 19:19.593
how we do things
outside the lab.

19:21.508 --> 19:23.205
- Why are we here?

19:23.249 --> 19:25.207
- Uh, Jasmine and Dylan met
in AA,

19:25.251 --> 19:27.209
so it seemed
a good place to start.

19:27.253 --> 19:30.169
- You know, my uncle's been
sober ten years 'cause of AA.

19:30.212 --> 19:33.084
This is, uh, kind of supposed
to be a safe space.

19:33.128 --> 19:36.218
- A woman was murdered
in her apartment, Rizwan.

19:36.262 --> 19:39.352
Sometimes safe spaces aren't
as safe as they seem.

19:44.574 --> 19:47.229
- So are we just gonna talk
to everyone here

19:47.273 --> 19:49.231
to see if anyone knows
who Jasmine's stalker is?

19:49.275 --> 19:50.319
- No.

19:50.363 --> 19:51.755
They're going to talk to us.

19:51.799 --> 19:54.367
Hear me. It's called
the cocktail party effect.

19:54.410 --> 19:56.369
You're in a crowd.
You're talking to one person.

19:56.412 --> 19:58.240
Everything else becomes
background noise

19:58.284 --> 20:01.504
until you hear something like
your name or the word "fire"

20:01.548 --> 20:03.898
or the word "sex."

20:03.941 --> 20:05.726
See?
Everyone hears the word "sex."

20:05.769 --> 20:08.729
In this case, we're gonna say
the name "Dylan" a few times.

20:08.772 --> 20:10.078
- Dylan?

20:10.121 --> 20:11.471
- Excellent job.

20:11.514 --> 20:13.081
And if Dylan's
friends are here,

20:13.124 --> 20:14.561
they'll come over
and talk to us,

20:14.604 --> 20:16.432
and we'll get some clues.

20:16.476 --> 20:17.433
Hm?

20:21.916 --> 20:22.917
- Heard you guys talking
about Dylan.

20:22.960 --> 20:23.961
- Are you a friend?

20:24.005 --> 20:25.876
- Oh, I'm his sponsor, Ray.

20:25.920 --> 20:26.877
This is Jeff.

20:26.921 --> 20:28.575
- Alec.

20:28.618 --> 20:30.577
- You don't mind me asking,
how'd you get the, uh--

20:30.620 --> 20:31.665
- Oh, this.

20:31.708 --> 20:33.101
Yeah, I--I got drunk.

20:33.144 --> 20:35.364
I tried to fix the oil burner.

20:35.408 --> 20:38.149
Burned down my house
and 60% of my body.

20:38.193 --> 20:40.587
- Jeez.
Talk about hitting bottom, huh?

20:40.630 --> 20:42.980
- I suppose you guys heard
that Dylan got arrested

20:43.024 --> 20:44.417
for killing Jasmine Curtland?

20:44.460 --> 20:46.288
- Yeah.
You know, it's hard to believe.

20:46.332 --> 20:48.072
I just didn't think
Dylan was the type.

20:48.116 --> 20:49.683
- Hey, Jeff.

20:49.726 --> 20:51.075
- Excuse me.

20:52.947 --> 20:54.427
- I feel like
I let the guy down.

20:54.470 --> 20:56.385
You know?
I should've been there for him.

20:56.429 --> 20:57.908
And maybe if I had been,
he wouldn't have--

20:57.952 --> 20:59.780
[phone ringing]

20:59.823 --> 21:01.216
- Excuse me.

21:01.260 --> 21:02.739
Alec here.

21:02.783 --> 21:04.654
- Professor,
it's Detective Chou.

21:04.698 --> 21:08.267
Listen, you might want
to swing by Jasmine's place.

21:08.310 --> 21:09.659
- Why? What's going on?

21:09.703 --> 21:12.053
- There's another suspect
in her murder.

21:12.096 --> 21:13.315
- [breathing shakily]

21:13.359 --> 21:15.839
I would never hurt Jasmine.

21:15.883 --> 21:17.188
She taught me so much.

21:17.232 --> 21:18.668
She inspired me.

21:18.712 --> 21:20.540
- Why'd you break in?

21:20.583 --> 21:23.978
- Because I wanted something
of hers to keep forever

21:24.021 --> 21:25.327
to remind me of her.

21:25.371 --> 21:27.547
It was stupid. I'm sorry.

21:31.028 --> 21:32.813
- So this is what you took?

21:32.856 --> 21:34.293
Lip gloss?

21:34.336 --> 21:36.295
Okay, we're gonna need
to take your statement.

21:37.948 --> 21:40.734
- That's the wrong lip gloss.

21:40.777 --> 21:41.865
- I'm sorry, what?

21:41.909 --> 21:43.345
- The--the cosmetic line

21:43.389 --> 21:45.782
that Jasmine endorses is
called Cinnamon.

21:47.218 --> 21:49.046
This is a different brand.

21:52.920 --> 21:55.052
This isn't hers, is it?

21:55.096 --> 21:58.447
Lila, I think I can get
the good police officers here

21:58.491 --> 22:01.668
to forget the last 20 minutes
ever happened

22:01.711 --> 22:06.194
if you tell me now
why you're really here.

22:06.237 --> 22:09.153
[tense music]

22:09.197 --> 22:11.504
- That bitch ruined my life.

22:11.547 --> 22:15.072
♪

22:18.249 --> 22:18.641
.

22:18.685 --> 22:21.209
- Okay, so I know I've only
been sober eight months.

22:21.252 --> 22:24.299
But part of being sober
is being honest.

22:24.343 --> 22:26.606
So I have to tell the truth.

22:26.649 --> 22:29.304
And I'm not knocking Lila.

22:29.348 --> 22:30.740
Okay? She's a nice girl.

22:30.784 --> 22:34.570
But I did some digging
into her product line,

22:34.614 --> 22:37.225
and they are tested
on animals.

22:37.268 --> 22:38.792
Lila says they're not.

22:38.835 --> 22:40.141
But they are.
I can only--

22:40.184 --> 22:42.186
- This better be good.
I had dinner plans.

22:42.230 --> 22:45.494
- She outed Lila
as a bunny killer and a liar.

22:45.538 --> 22:48.192
- Influencers can get very
competitive with one another.

22:48.236 --> 22:50.586
- She admitted to writing
threatening notes to Jasmine.

22:50.630 --> 22:51.805
That's why she broke in here,

22:51.848 --> 22:53.110
to keep the police
from finding them.

22:53.154 --> 22:54.677
- I wouldn't call that
a motive for murder.

22:54.721 --> 22:56.636
The FBI is going
through Jasmine's laptop

22:56.679 --> 22:58.028
for any other correspondence.

22:58.072 --> 22:59.900
But her alibi seems
to check out.

22:59.943 --> 23:01.989
- What will you do about Dylan?

23:02.032 --> 23:03.947
- Most likely, we'll be
filing in the morning.

23:03.991 --> 23:05.296
- It's possible
that Lila wasn't

23:05.340 --> 23:07.473
the only person burned
by Jasmine's influence.

23:07.516 --> 23:10.127
- We also have an ex-boyfriend
who says he killed her.

23:10.171 --> 23:13.130
[intriguing music]

23:13.174 --> 23:15.176
- Was Lila in AA?

23:15.219 --> 23:16.569
- Not that I know of.

23:16.612 --> 23:18.832
- The police found
a five-year sobriety chip here

23:18.875 --> 23:20.050
the day Jasmine was killed.

23:20.094 --> 23:21.748
She said she'd been sober
for eight months.

23:21.791 --> 23:24.881
- Maybe it was Dylan's.
- Yeah, maybe.

23:24.925 --> 23:26.579
- Why are you so sure
he's innocent?

23:26.622 --> 23:28.102
- I'm not sure about anything,

23:28.145 --> 23:30.452
and I don't think
you should be either.

23:30.496 --> 23:37.633
♪

23:43.422 --> 23:44.727
Oh, right.

23:51.255 --> 23:53.519
Hi.

23:53.562 --> 23:55.651
- Hi.
- I was just wondering,

23:55.695 --> 23:58.175
uh, did any prints show up

23:58.219 --> 24:00.917
on that sobriety chip
from Jasmine's place?

24:00.961 --> 24:02.266
- I can--I can check
with the techs.

24:02.310 --> 24:04.704
They're going
through her laptop.

24:04.747 --> 24:06.749
Is that really why you came by?

24:06.793 --> 24:08.055
- Can I come in?

24:13.103 --> 24:14.365
Oh, wow.

24:15.889 --> 24:17.891
I like what you've done
in here.

24:17.934 --> 24:19.066
- You don't have to say that.

24:19.109 --> 24:20.546
- No, I do.

24:20.589 --> 24:22.504
The walls look better
this color.

24:22.548 --> 24:24.114
- Alec.

24:24.158 --> 24:25.420
What's up?

24:25.464 --> 24:27.291
- [exhales deeply]

24:32.471 --> 24:33.646
- It's Dylan, isn't it?

24:35.386 --> 24:37.737
His trauma is bringing
all your trauma back.

24:37.780 --> 24:39.086
- Come on, Marisa.

24:39.129 --> 24:41.175
- What he went through
in Afghanistan?

24:41.218 --> 24:44.483
He survived
while his friends died,

24:44.526 --> 24:46.136
just like you.

24:48.574 --> 24:50.967
The nightmares, are they back?

24:51.011 --> 24:53.666
- I've had a nightmare or two.
- Mm-hmm.

24:53.709 --> 24:54.971
You talk to Dr. Stevens?

24:55.015 --> 24:57.844
- I know everything he knows
and then some.

24:57.887 --> 25:01.108
- [scoffs] Do you find it
the least bit ironic

25:01.151 --> 25:03.589
that the behavioral psych
professor won't see

25:03.632 --> 25:05.199
a damn psychologist?

25:05.242 --> 25:07.767
You are never gonna
get closure on the past

25:07.810 --> 25:09.464
unless you deal with it
in the present.

25:09.508 --> 25:11.031
- Well, in the present,

25:11.074 --> 25:14.295
Wes Banning's
parole hearing is this week.

25:21.650 --> 25:23.130
- We both knew
this day would come.

25:23.173 --> 25:25.219
- Any chance
they'd let him out?

25:25.262 --> 25:26.742
- I don't know.

25:30.790 --> 25:31.791
You gonna go?

25:31.834 --> 25:32.966
- I have to.

25:33.009 --> 25:34.968
My injuries could sway
the parole board.

25:35.011 --> 25:36.796
It's the identifiable victim
effect.

25:36.839 --> 25:39.494
- Alec.
- I--I am the only one

25:39.538 --> 25:41.452
who canbe there, Marisa.

25:41.496 --> 25:42.889
I owe it to the ones who can't.

25:42.932 --> 25:44.325
- I understand.

25:44.368 --> 25:45.326
- I know you do.

25:45.369 --> 25:47.502
It was your case too.

25:47.546 --> 25:49.460
- My first one.

25:49.504 --> 25:50.592
- [chuckles]

25:50.636 --> 25:52.507
You were not what I expected

25:52.551 --> 25:55.075
when they told me
the FBI wanted to talk to me.

25:55.118 --> 25:57.164
- Oh, no?
What did you expect?

25:57.207 --> 25:59.340
- I don't know, some old
white dude with a mustache.

25:59.383 --> 26:02.038
- [laughs] We must have been
fresh out of mustaches.

26:02.082 --> 26:04.127
[soft dramatic music]

26:04.171 --> 26:05.999
- I guess now
you wish you hadn't

26:06.042 --> 26:07.870
drawn the short straw
on that day, huh?

26:07.914 --> 26:10.394
♪

26:10.438 --> 26:11.613
- [echoing] I'm Agent Clark.

26:11.657 --> 26:13.920
Alec, whatever happened,

26:13.963 --> 26:15.835
whatever will happen,

26:15.878 --> 26:18.925
I will never regret
the day that we met

26:18.968 --> 26:21.449
or anything after that.

26:21.492 --> 26:22.755
[phone buzzes and chimes]

26:25.932 --> 26:27.673
They found something
on Jasmine's laptop.

26:27.716 --> 26:29.588
They're sending it now.

26:29.631 --> 26:32.591
- I know anonymity is sacred.

26:32.634 --> 26:35.681
Lives can be ruined
when I name names.

26:35.724 --> 26:37.508
But what about my life?

26:37.552 --> 26:40.207
I told him that we weren't
right for each other,

26:40.250 --> 26:43.210
but he just couldn't take no
for an answer.

26:43.253 --> 26:46.039
AA saved me,
and because of him,

26:46.082 --> 26:47.910
it wasn't safe anymore.

26:47.954 --> 26:50.217
I had stopped going
to meetings.

26:50.260 --> 26:51.479
[knocking]

26:52.915 --> 26:54.482
[sighs]
I--

26:54.525 --> 26:57.180
I guess I'll tell you guys
about it tomorrow.

26:57.224 --> 26:59.879
- It was on her hard drive.

26:59.922 --> 27:01.532
She never got a chance
to upload it

27:01.576 --> 27:03.709
because she was killed
shortly after.

27:03.752 --> 27:05.232
- Which is when Dylan arrived.

27:05.275 --> 27:08.278
- It's like I said,
it's always the boyfriend.

27:12.979 --> 27:13.370
.

27:13.414 --> 27:15.851
- Charges have been filed today
against Dylan Hayes,

27:15.895 --> 27:17.679
son of Senator Laura Hayes,

27:17.723 --> 27:19.594
in the murder
of his ex-girlfriend,

27:19.638 --> 27:23.076
social media influencer
Jasmine Curtland.

27:23.119 --> 27:25.818
[buzzer blares]

27:27.950 --> 27:28.864
- Oh, it's you.

27:30.736 --> 27:32.607
You got more weird
sex questions?

27:32.651 --> 27:34.696
- Dylan, how long
have you been sober?

27:34.740 --> 27:36.002
- Almost six months.

27:36.045 --> 27:37.917
- So you don't have
a five-year sobriety chip?

27:37.960 --> 27:39.353
- No. Why?

27:39.396 --> 27:40.571
- Dylan, this is important.

27:40.615 --> 27:42.617
Is there anyone else in AA

27:42.661 --> 27:44.924
that might have had
something against Jasmine?

27:44.967 --> 27:46.316
- I don't know.

27:46.360 --> 27:49.363
- Everyone thinks
you're guilty, Dylan.

27:49.406 --> 27:51.757
You realize I'm probably
your best shot here, right?

27:51.800 --> 27:53.367
- Why are you helping me?

27:53.410 --> 27:55.978
- Because--because I think
you're innocent.

27:56.022 --> 27:57.371
- I'm not.

27:57.414 --> 27:58.633
- Of course you feel
guilty about what happened

27:58.677 --> 28:00.156
in the war,
but that has nothing to do

28:00.200 --> 28:01.418
with what happened to Jasmine.

28:01.462 --> 28:03.638
But don't worry.
If I'm wrong,

28:03.682 --> 28:04.813
there's an excellent chance
you're going to jail.

28:04.857 --> 28:07.163
But if I'm right
and you don't help me,

28:07.207 --> 28:11.385
most likely, no one's gonna
find out who really killed her.

28:16.607 --> 28:18.740
- She stopped coming
to St. Mel's.

28:18.784 --> 28:20.176
- How come?

28:20.220 --> 28:21.482
- She said something
about some guy

28:21.525 --> 28:23.397
who kept hitting on her
at meetings.

28:23.440 --> 28:24.746
I didn't think
it was a big deal.

28:24.790 --> 28:26.356
[tense music]

28:26.400 --> 28:28.228
- Did she say anything else
about him?

28:28.271 --> 28:30.491
Anything at all?

28:30.534 --> 28:32.798
- Only that he came
to every meeting.

28:32.841 --> 28:34.234
He was a regular.

28:34.277 --> 28:40.893
♪

28:41.981 --> 28:43.504
- Rizwan.

28:43.547 --> 28:45.201
- My uncle's gonna
want this back.

28:45.245 --> 28:47.029
- A man's life is at stake.

28:47.073 --> 28:48.944
I'm sure he'll understand.

28:48.988 --> 28:51.251
- So what's the plan?
More cocktail party effect?

28:51.294 --> 28:53.296
- Not exactly.
Tell me what you know

28:53.340 --> 28:54.689
about reciprocity.

28:54.733 --> 28:57.605
- Uh, chapter six,
your second book.

28:57.648 --> 29:00.564
Uh, if someone shares
something intimate or private,

29:00.608 --> 29:02.349
you feel a strong obligation
to share back.

29:02.392 --> 29:03.785
- You've done your homework.

29:03.829 --> 29:06.353
Reciprocity is
a very strong instinct.

29:06.396 --> 29:08.659
Programs like AA depend
on this concept,

29:08.703 --> 29:10.487
whether they know it or not.

29:13.229 --> 29:14.840
Hi. I'm Alec.

29:14.883 --> 29:16.580
all: Hi, Alec.

29:18.278 --> 29:22.543
- If you're wondering
about my face,

29:22.586 --> 29:25.198
I don't talk much
about how it happened.

29:25.241 --> 29:26.852
[soft dramatic music]

29:26.895 --> 29:30.029
Because the truth is,

29:30.072 --> 29:31.421
I don't remember it--

29:31.465 --> 29:33.162
not the important parts,
anyway.

29:33.206 --> 29:34.729
♪

29:34.773 --> 29:36.644
- Admit it.
You were impressed.

29:36.687 --> 29:39.038
- Well, maybe not
impressed exactly.

29:39.081 --> 29:40.082
- Really?

29:40.126 --> 29:42.868
[ominous music]

29:42.911 --> 29:44.173
I forgot my backpack.

29:44.217 --> 29:45.653
I'll be right back.

29:53.922 --> 29:55.663
- [coughing]

29:58.492 --> 30:03.323
I usually make up stories
about the scars.

30:03.366 --> 30:04.977
Car accident,

30:05.020 --> 30:07.327
cooking incident,

30:07.370 --> 30:09.633
oil burner mishap.

30:09.677 --> 30:12.549
But it's just a way
to avoid the truth.

30:12.593 --> 30:15.422
I can still hear the blast.

30:15.465 --> 30:18.729
I can still smell
the explosives.

30:18.773 --> 30:21.254
I can still feel the searing,
scorching pain

30:21.297 --> 30:22.995
of fire on my skin.

30:23.038 --> 30:28.348
But I can't recall
a single damn thing

30:28.391 --> 30:30.045
about the bomber.

30:30.089 --> 30:32.395
All those people died.

30:32.439 --> 30:34.571
I should've died.

30:34.615 --> 30:36.617
And the person responsible
could walk free

30:36.660 --> 30:39.881
because I can't remember.

30:43.406 --> 30:44.755
Good to see you, man.

30:44.799 --> 30:46.540
- So, uh, you didn't, like,

30:46.583 --> 30:48.020
make all that up, did you?

30:48.063 --> 30:49.848
- Of course not.

30:49.891 --> 30:50.805
- I knew that.

30:51.980 --> 30:54.722
- Hey, uh,
hell of a story, man.

30:54.765 --> 30:57.203
- It is.
Uh, I was surprised

30:57.246 --> 30:58.900
how cathartic it was
to share it.

30:58.944 --> 31:01.468
- There's something I've been
wanting to talk about myself.

31:01.511 --> 31:02.904
D-do you got a minute?

31:02.948 --> 31:04.950
- Of course.
That's why we're here, right?

31:04.993 --> 31:07.517
- So the thing is, if I hadn't
gone to that birthday party

31:07.561 --> 31:10.172
when I was seven years old,
I figure my whole life

31:10.216 --> 31:11.347
turns out differently,
you know?

31:11.391 --> 31:12.609
- But hey, you're sober now.

31:12.653 --> 31:14.220
That's all that matters.

31:14.263 --> 31:15.830
Have you reached
your five-year mark yet?

31:15.874 --> 31:17.266
- Five? No.

31:17.310 --> 31:19.399
This summer,
it'll be my one-year.

31:19.442 --> 31:21.314
Nah, the only guy
I know here who's, uh--

31:21.357 --> 31:24.099
who's past five years is, um...

31:24.143 --> 31:26.319
Ray.

31:26.362 --> 31:27.276
- Will you excuse me
for a second?

31:27.320 --> 31:28.495
- Yeah.

31:28.538 --> 31:31.193
[tense music]

31:31.237 --> 31:32.803
- Hey, Ray.

31:32.847 --> 31:34.762
I believe you dropped this.

31:34.805 --> 31:35.806
- Oh.

31:35.850 --> 31:37.330
Thank you.

31:37.373 --> 31:39.114
I was looking for that.

31:40.202 --> 31:41.551
- Call my ex-wife

31:41.595 --> 31:42.944
and tell her to get here
as soon as she can.

31:42.988 --> 31:44.163
- Okay.

31:44.206 --> 31:50.865
♪

31:54.651 --> 31:57.132
You know, you don't appreciate
remote car keys

31:57.176 --> 31:58.699
until you have a car
that doesn't have one.

31:58.742 --> 32:00.266
- That's an amazing ride.

32:00.309 --> 32:01.702
You like it?

32:01.745 --> 32:03.312
- Thought it would help me
get over my divorce.

32:03.356 --> 32:05.532
- Mm. Didn't work?

32:05.575 --> 32:08.100
- [sighs] It mostly reminds me
of what I'm trying to get over.

32:10.189 --> 32:11.712
Hey.

32:11.755 --> 32:13.801
I went to see Dylan.

32:13.844 --> 32:16.238
He told me that he doesn't even

32:16.282 --> 32:17.979
actually remember
shooting Jasmine.

32:18.023 --> 32:19.459
Made me think
of how crazy memory is.

32:19.502 --> 32:21.548
Your memory ever play tricks
on you?

32:21.591 --> 32:22.549
- Not that I know of.

32:22.592 --> 32:24.507
- Mine does.

32:24.551 --> 32:28.381
For years, I remember the day
I was burned being a Sunday.

32:28.424 --> 32:30.905
I found out later
it was a Saturday.

32:30.949 --> 32:33.125
I don't know why that matters,
not really.

32:33.168 --> 32:35.736
I wonder how Dylan feels,
about to go to jail

32:35.779 --> 32:38.565
for something
he doesn't even remember.

32:40.915 --> 32:43.004
You know, they never found
the murder weapon.

32:46.399 --> 32:48.270
Oh.

32:48.314 --> 32:49.619
That's where it went.

32:53.014 --> 32:53.232
.

32:53.275 --> 32:56.365
[dramatic music]

32:56.409 --> 32:58.454
- Do you have a plan for how
you'll dispose of my body?

32:58.498 --> 33:00.195
- Don't start
that shrink crap with me.

33:00.239 --> 33:02.154
I know who you are.
I saw you on the news.

33:02.197 --> 33:03.155
You working with the cops?

33:03.198 --> 33:04.895
- If I say yes, do you kill me?

33:04.939 --> 33:06.114
I don't mind dying very much,

33:06.158 --> 33:08.116
but I've never had
the opportunity

33:08.160 --> 33:10.423
to do a study like this,
so I have to ask.

33:10.466 --> 33:13.339
Are you considering all
the pros and cons right now?

33:13.382 --> 33:14.862
We can talk it through
if it helps.

33:14.905 --> 33:17.778
I happen to be an expert
at making better decisions.

33:17.821 --> 33:18.997
- How about you stop talking?

33:19.040 --> 33:20.911
- If you kill me,
I stop talking.

33:20.955 --> 33:21.956
That's a pro.

33:22.000 --> 33:24.045
My ex-wife would agree
with you.

33:24.089 --> 33:26.482
The con though is, without me,

33:26.526 --> 33:28.093
you're really on your own
with the police.

33:28.136 --> 33:29.877
- I'm warning you.
- I just want you

33:29.920 --> 33:32.749
to ask yourself if you're
making the best choice here.

33:32.793 --> 33:33.750
- Shut up.

33:33.794 --> 33:35.622
[tires squealing]

33:35.665 --> 33:38.277
- [grunts]
You're obviously a smart guy,

33:38.320 --> 33:40.409
the way you framed Dylan
for Jasmine's death.

33:40.453 --> 33:41.932
- I just wanted her
to go out with me.

33:41.976 --> 33:43.064
She kept saying no.

33:43.108 --> 33:44.283
- Probably an indicator

33:44.326 --> 33:46.154
that she didn't want
to go out with you.

33:47.808 --> 33:49.810
- I liked her.
And she would have liked me too

33:49.853 --> 33:50.985
if she had just given me
a chance.

33:51.029 --> 33:52.073
- But she didn't, did she?

33:52.117 --> 33:53.553
- She said she was gonna
tell Dylan,

33:53.596 --> 33:54.989
that she was gonna
tell everyone.

33:55.033 --> 33:56.686
She was gonna go online,

33:56.730 --> 33:59.080
say that I was
some kind of predator.

33:59.124 --> 34:03.606
You know, before AA,
I was a worthless drunk.

34:03.650 --> 34:06.174
Now I'm getting certified to be
a substance abuse counselor.

34:06.218 --> 34:08.132
Things were finally starting
to go right.

34:09.830 --> 34:11.571
- You couldn't have killed her
after you left Dylan

34:11.614 --> 34:13.268
because the FBI checked
your alibi.

34:13.312 --> 34:15.444
So you must have
killed her before.

34:15.487 --> 34:17.533
You didn't bring a weapon,

34:17.577 --> 34:20.536
so you probably didn't plan
to actually kill her.

34:20.580 --> 34:22.321
So what happened?
You threaten her?

34:22.364 --> 34:23.757
- I didn't pull out
the gun, okay?

34:23.800 --> 34:25.063
She did.

34:25.106 --> 34:26.803
- Obviously, you got it
out of her hand

34:26.847 --> 34:27.978
and into yours.

34:28.022 --> 34:30.416
♪

34:30.458 --> 34:32.244
You didn't know how you were
gonna get out of it.

34:33.505 --> 34:36.030
Then you thought of Dylan.

34:36.074 --> 34:39.077
You knew the police would
suspect the ex-boyfriend.

34:39.120 --> 34:40.339
You drug his drink.

34:42.601 --> 34:45.822
You put the sweatshirt
in his car.

34:45.866 --> 34:49.130
As his sponsor, you would've
been his first call.

34:49.174 --> 34:50.827
He trusted you completely,

34:50.871 --> 34:53.482
and you abused that trust
to protect yourself.

34:53.525 --> 34:55.397
Made him think he'd relapsed,

34:55.440 --> 34:57.312
helped him "remember."

34:57.356 --> 34:59.401
Everything Dylan told
the police,

34:59.445 --> 35:02.012
you planted into his head.

35:02.056 --> 35:04.232
Dylan didn't have a beer,
did he?

35:04.276 --> 35:07.017
He didn't even go
to Jasmine's, did he?

35:07.061 --> 35:08.454
- She was gonna ruin my life.

35:08.497 --> 35:10.847
- So you took hers
and ruined Dylan's.

35:10.891 --> 35:14.068
[siren wailing]

35:16.070 --> 35:18.638
You're either gonna kill me
or go to jail, probably both.

35:18.681 --> 35:20.161
So you may as well tell me
if I got it right.

35:20.205 --> 35:22.163
- Yeah. All but one thing.

35:22.207 --> 35:23.556
I'm not going to jail.

35:23.599 --> 35:25.601
♪

35:25.645 --> 35:26.776
[gunshots]

35:35.742 --> 35:42.705
♪

35:52.715 --> 35:55.065
- [groans softly]

35:55.109 --> 35:56.415
- Hey.

36:00.027 --> 36:02.203
- Hey.
- Hey.

36:02.247 --> 36:04.074
- Did you take him alive?
- Mm-hmm.

36:04.118 --> 36:06.076
- The car?

36:06.120 --> 36:07.600
- Totaled.
- [groans]

36:07.643 --> 36:09.906
- What were you thinking,
running after him like that?

36:09.950 --> 36:12.387
- It's not every day that I get
to talk to a criminal

36:12.431 --> 36:14.346
before he commits
another crime.

36:14.389 --> 36:16.043
I thought I could help him
make a better decision.

36:16.086 --> 36:17.697
- Of course you did.

36:17.740 --> 36:19.742
- I was making headway
until you showed up.

36:19.786 --> 36:22.876
- You still think that
because you cheated death once,

36:22.919 --> 36:24.443
you can do it again.

36:24.486 --> 36:25.748
- Mm, mm.
- Mm, yeah.

36:25.792 --> 36:26.923
- Hey there.

36:26.967 --> 36:29.187
Oh, I didn't mean to interrupt.

36:29.230 --> 36:31.232
Just wanted to see
how you're feeling.

36:31.276 --> 36:32.581
- I've been better.

36:32.625 --> 36:34.104
But then, I've been worse too.

36:34.148 --> 36:35.715
- I can attest to that.

36:35.758 --> 36:36.759
[phone rings]

36:40.720 --> 36:43.549
- I just wanted to let you know
Dylan's been released.

36:43.592 --> 36:45.594
All the charges have
been dropped.

36:45.638 --> 36:46.769
- That's good.

36:46.813 --> 36:48.162
That's good. I'm glad.

36:48.206 --> 36:49.685
- Would you ever consider

36:49.729 --> 36:51.513
doing some work
for our department?

36:53.080 --> 36:54.473
- You have my number.

36:56.214 --> 36:58.259
- Hope you feel better soon.

36:59.304 --> 37:00.696
- [chuckles]

37:00.740 --> 37:02.176
I see you.

37:03.351 --> 37:04.744
You are a magnet

37:04.787 --> 37:07.268
for powerful women
in law enforcement.

37:07.312 --> 37:08.530
- What are you talking about?

37:08.574 --> 37:10.445
I'm not interested in Elise.

37:10.489 --> 37:13.405
- Mm, because you're still
in love with your ex-wife.

37:13.448 --> 37:16.756
And no car or hot DA
is gonna change that.

37:16.799 --> 37:18.410
- You think she's hot?

37:18.453 --> 37:20.412
- Yeah, a little bit.

37:20.455 --> 37:22.892
But she's got nothing
on the OG.

37:24.242 --> 37:26.461
Endgame?

37:26.505 --> 37:28.507
I'm still shipping you two.

37:30.204 --> 37:31.988
- [grunts]

37:32.032 --> 37:34.991
[intriguing music]

37:35.035 --> 37:41.911
♪

37:43.173 --> 37:45.219
[tires squeal]

38:09.330 --> 38:10.505
- Dylan.

38:10.549 --> 38:12.290
Come on in. Have a seat.

38:12.333 --> 38:14.814
- I just wanted to thank you.

38:14.857 --> 38:16.859
I could have gone to jail
for the rest of my life

38:16.903 --> 38:18.296
if you hadn't stepped in.

38:19.732 --> 38:22.256
- I'm sorry for what happened
to you, man.

38:24.389 --> 38:26.565
- I still remember doing it.

38:28.262 --> 38:29.698
How can that be?

38:29.742 --> 38:35.051
- Memory is the great conman
of human nature, Dylan.

38:35.095 --> 38:36.879
It lies to us.

38:36.923 --> 38:38.141
It's lied to me.

38:38.185 --> 38:41.362
Memory and imagination work
the same way.

38:41.406 --> 38:44.104
Once Ray planted those lies
in your mind,

38:44.147 --> 38:48.282
your brain was no longer able
to distinguish between the two.

38:48.326 --> 38:49.718
- So how do I make it go away?

38:49.762 --> 38:51.981
- Imagine something else
happened.

38:52.025 --> 38:54.549
And think about that every day
for a hundred days.

38:54.593 --> 38:56.508
Eventually,
the bad memories fade.

38:56.551 --> 38:58.379
They're replaced
with better ones.

38:58.423 --> 39:00.903
- And that--does it work?

39:00.947 --> 39:02.731
- For some.

39:04.080 --> 39:09.259
You know, it works
for the other memories too,

39:09.303 --> 39:10.957
of Afghanistan.

39:11.000 --> 39:14.439
The ones you tried
to drown with alcohol.

39:14.482 --> 39:17.790
You can't just try
not to drink.

39:17.833 --> 39:19.269
You have to replace it
with something else

39:19.313 --> 39:21.141
that helps you move forward.

39:21.184 --> 39:25.058
For me, it was my work.

39:28.627 --> 39:30.324
- I've been meaning
to go back to school.

39:30.368 --> 39:31.760
- Maybe give that a try.

39:31.804 --> 39:33.632
You know, I hear
the psych department

39:33.675 --> 39:35.024
at Wylton's not so bad.

39:35.068 --> 39:36.069
- [laughs softly]

39:36.112 --> 39:39.028
[soft dramatic music]

39:39.072 --> 39:44.556
♪

39:44.599 --> 39:46.993
- Name and DOC number, please.

39:50.170 --> 39:52.128
- Uh, Wes Banning,

39:52.172 --> 39:54.304
A4261.

39:54.348 --> 39:55.871
- I'm going to read
some information

39:55.915 --> 39:57.046
for the record now.

39:57.090 --> 39:59.440
The Virginia Parole Board
will consider

39:59.484 --> 40:02.225
an independent quality
conditional release

40:02.269 --> 40:05.272
of all adult offenders
who petition for pardons--

40:05.315 --> 40:07.100
- You came.

40:07.143 --> 40:08.449
- Wouldn't be anywhere else.

40:08.493 --> 40:10.886
- Protection of society
by facilitating,

40:10.930 --> 40:13.454
as appropriate,
the timely integration

40:13.498 --> 40:16.588
of offenders back into society.

40:16.631 --> 40:19.329
Would you like to make
a statement, Mr. Banning?

40:19.373 --> 40:20.505
- Yes, I would.

40:24.204 --> 40:26.902
Um...

40:26.946 --> 40:30.558
to the family members
that are here,

40:30.602 --> 40:33.779
I'd like to say I'm sorry
for what I did.

40:33.822 --> 40:36.825
I take full responsibility
for my actions.

40:36.869 --> 40:38.697
[door opens]
And I've learned

40:38.740 --> 40:40.481
from my time in prison.

40:40.525 --> 40:43.484
[eerie music]

40:43.528 --> 40:50.230
♪

40:50.273 --> 40:52.014
- If you are released,

40:52.058 --> 40:55.148
do you think you'd be likely
to commit crimes again?

41:01.067 --> 41:02.111
- Yes.

41:02.155 --> 41:03.678
[indistinct chatter]

41:03.722 --> 41:06.812
I'm kind of a bad seed,
to tell you the truth.

41:06.855 --> 41:08.335
If you let me out,
I'll probably bomb

41:08.378 --> 41:11.077
another couple churches.

41:11.120 --> 41:12.557
- Given the lack of remorse

41:12.600 --> 41:14.820
and intent
to commit other crimes,

41:14.863 --> 41:17.518
this board has no choice
but to deny

41:17.562 --> 41:19.085
the petitioner's request
for parole.

41:19.128 --> 41:22.088
[dramatic music]

41:22.131 --> 41:23.350
♪

41:23.393 --> 41:25.221
[tires squeal]

41:25.265 --> 41:30.400
♪

41:30.444 --> 41:32.533
- Did you see his face?

41:32.577 --> 41:34.622
The plates?
- No, nothing.

41:34.666 --> 41:36.972
- Whoever that was
scared Banning so much

41:37.016 --> 41:38.452
that he'd rather stay
behind bars.

41:38.496 --> 41:39.845
- Banning wasn't a lone wolf.

41:39.888 --> 41:41.586
- Someone else is
pulling the strings.

41:41.629 --> 41:43.936
And whoever it is,
is still out there.

41:43.979 --> 41:48.767
♪
